Here's my analysis of performance issues, ordered by impact in a hot-path CMS scenario:

---

### 🔴 Critical — Redundant re-processing

**Line 187 — `Pascalize` re-calls `Humanize`:**
```csharp
return input.Humanize().Transform(To.TitleCase).Replace(" ", "");
```
And `Dehumanize` (line 171) calls `word.Humanize().Pascalize()`, so **every word is `Humanize()`-d twice**. With hundreds of strings this doubles the regex/allocation work.

---

### 🟠 High — Avoidable allocations on every call

| Lines | Issue |
|-------|-------|
| **86–98** | `.Cast<Match>().Select(...)` — LINQ chain allocates enumerator + delegate per call. A `for` loop over `MatchCollection` avoids this. |
| **93** | `value.All(char.IsUpper)` — LINQ enumerator over `string` chars. A manual loop is zero-alloc. |
| **97** | `value.ToLower()` — allocates a new string *per regex match*. Also culture-sensitive (non-deterministic perf). |
| **101** | `result.All(c => ...)` — second LINQ enumeration over the full result string. |
| **106** | `char.ToUpper(result[0]) + result[1..]` — `result[1..]` allocates a substring, then `char + string` boxes. The file's own `Concat(char, ReadOnlySpan<char>)` helper (line 128) exists but is unused here. |
| **171** | `string.Concat(words.Select(...))` — LINQ enumerator + delegate allocation. |
| **213** | `params IStringTransformer[]` — allocates a `T[]` on every `Transform` call, even for the common 1-transformer case. `Aggregate` adds another enumerator. |

---

### 🟡 Medium — Unnecessary work

| Lines | Issue |
|-------|-------|
| **55** | `FreestandingSpacingCharRegex().IsMatch(input)` runs a regex on *every* call to check if input is only whitespace — almost never true. A manual `char.IsWhiteSpace` loop short-circuits faster. |
| **75** | `input.Split(['_', '-'])` — the char-array collection expression may allocate per call (pre-.NET 9). `string.Split` itself allocates a `string[]`. |
| **187** | `.Replace(" ", "")` — third intermediate string allocation in the chain; could fold into the title-casing step. |

---

### 🟢 Architectural — No memoization

A CMS re-rendering pages will call `Humanize("PublishedDate")` hundreds of times with the **same inputs**. A small `ConcurrentDictionary<string, string>` cache would eliminate all repeated work. The input space (field/property names) is finite and small, making this safe.

---

### Recommended fix for `FromPascalCase` (highest-impact single change)

```csharp
internal static string FromPascalCase(string input)
{
    var matches = PascalCaseWordPartsRegex().Matches(input);
    if (matches.Count == 0) return input;

    var sb = new ValueStringBuilder(stackalloc char[128]);
    for (int i = 0; i < matches.Count; i++)
    {
        if (i > 0) sb.Append(' ');
        var value = matches[i].ValueSpan;
        bool allUpper = true;
        foreach (var c in value) { if (!char.IsUpper(c)) { allUpper = false; break; } }

        if (allUpper && (value.Length > 1
            || (matches[i].Index > 0 && input[matches[i].Index - 1] == ' ')
            || value is "I"))
        {
            sb.Append(value);
        }
        else
        {
            foreach (var c in value) sb.Append(char.ToLowerInvariant(c));
        }
    }
    // ... capitalize first char, check all-upper
}
```

This eliminates LINQ, per-match `ToLower()` allocations, and the substring on the final line. Want me to implement the full set of fixes?
